econdary lymphoid structures. Typically, T cells specific for immunodominant gluten peptides derived from alpha- and omega-gliadins are consistently found in patients (Christofersen et al., 2014). Furthermore, these T cells often express public T cell receptors, characterized by shared features across patients.&nbsp;  A hallmark of adaptive T cell responses is the clonal expansion of reactive T cells (Jabri &amp; Sollid, 2017). The absence of detectable gluten-specific T cells in healthy controls may result from their low frequency compared to the expanded pool of such T cells in patients. Alternatively, because T cell repertoire generation is a stochastic process, it is possible that the public gluten-reactive T cell receptors were not produced in controls.&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:11:02 +0000 2026"}